  "prompt": "How did Oliver Sykes damaged his voice exactly?",
  "response": "Oliver Sykes, the lead vocalist of the band Bring Me The Horizon, has experienced vocal issues over the years due to the intense demands of his singing style. While there isn't a single, specific incident that \"damaged\" his voice, several factors likely contributed to the strain and wear on his vocal cords:\n\n1. **Screaming and Harsh Vocals**: Sykes' early work with Bring Me The Horizon heavily featured screaming and growling, which can be extremely taxing on the vocal cords if not done with proper technique.\n\n2. **Lack of Vocal Training**: In the early days of the band, Sykes may not have had formal vocal training, which can lead to improper technique and increased risk of vocal damage.\n\n3. **Touring and Overuse**: Extensive touring and performing without adequate rest can lead to vocal fatigue and strain, especially when combined with demanding vocal techniques.\n\n4. **Dehydration and Poor Vocal Care**: Factors like dehydration, smoking, and not warming up properly can exacerbate vocal strain.\n\n5. **Evolution of Singing Style**: As Bring Me The Horizon's sound evolved, Sykes incorporated more clean singing into his repertoire. Transitioning between screaming and singing, especially without proper technique, can be challenging and stressful on the vocal cords.\n\nOver time, Sykes has openly discussed these challenges and worked with vocal coaches to improve his technique and preserve his voice. This has allowed him to adapt his singing style and continue performing, even as the band's music has shifted toward a more melodic and less scream-heavy sound.",
